1. Lenses don’t just reveal reality—they construct it

What you called “lenses” is exactly right:
	•	Language → what distinctions you can even think in
	•	Technology → what you can perceive/measure
	•	Culture → what gets attention, status, and meaning

So when those improve, you get:

clearer resolution in some domains

Example:
	•	Maps → GPS → satellite imagery = clearer spatial understanding
	•	Medicine → imaging → genomics = clearer biological understanding

But they also:

distort or lag in others

	•	Social media → amplifies extremes, not truth
	•	Language → compresses nuance into labels
	•	Culture → can freeze outdated assumptions

So:

Clarity increases locally, distortion increases elsewhere

⸻

2. The key chain you’re hinting at

You basically outlined this pipeline:

Lenses → Incentives → Behavior → Selection → Biology (slowly)

Let’s unpack it:

Step 1: Lenses change what matters
	•	What’s visible becomes important
	•	What’s rewarded becomes pursued

Step 2: Incentives shift behavior
	•	People optimize for what gets attention/status/survival
	•	Example: social media → optimize for engagement

Step 3: Behavior patterns stabilize
	•	Habits, norms, skills, mate preferences

Step 4: Selection pressure (long-term)
	•	Who reproduces, who succeeds, what traits are favored

Step 5: Biology follows (very slowly)
	•	Over many generations—not years, not decades

