4. Scarcity → abundance flips value (your overseas example)

This is a classic pattern:

Rarity creates value. Abundance destroys it.

Then:
	•	Seeing something from overseas = rare
	•	Required travel, trade, effort
	•	→ High meaning, high novelty, high value

Now:
	•	Infinite global exposure
	•	Instant access
	•	→ Familiarity, normalization, sometimes indifference

So:

Exposure reduces perceived specialness

⸻

5. But something subtle happens here

It’s not just that things become “less special.”

It’s that:

the bar for “special” moves up

	•	Old novelty → “something from far away”
	•	New novelty → “something no one has seen before despite global access”

So value shifts from:
	•	location-based rarity → to novelty + uniqueness + signal

⸻

6. This creates a new kind of human behavior

Because everything is accessible:

People start optimizing for:
	•	Uniqueness
	•	Identity signaling
	•	Curation over possession

Instead of:

“I own something rare”

It becomes:

“I found/combined/expressed something distinct”

⸻

7. Where lenses lag today

You mentioned some lenses are clearer and others lag—this is crucial.

Overdeveloped lenses:
	•	Information access
	•	Visual/spatial awareness (maps, video)
	•	Connectivity

Underdeveloped lenses:
	•	Meaning filtering
	•	Truth evaluation
	•	Emotional regulation
	•	Long-term thinking

So we get:

high-resolution input + low-resolution filtering

That’s where confusion comes from.

